[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] In computing, a **benchmark** is the act of running a computer program, a set of programs, or other operations, in order to assess the relative performance of an object, normally by running a number of standard tests and trials against it.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] The term *benchmark* is also commonly utilized for the purposes of elaborately designed benchmarking programs themselves.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Benchmarking is usually associated with assessing performance characteristics of computer hardware, for example, the floating point operation performance of a CPU, but there are circumstances when the technique is also applicable to software.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Software benchmarks are, for example, run against compilers or database management systems (DBMS).
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks provide a method of comparing the performance of various subsystems across different chip/system architectures.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Benchmarking as a part of continuous integration is called Continuous Benchmarking.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] As computer architecture advanced, it became more difficult to compare the performance of various computer systems simply by looking at their specifications.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Therefore, tests were developed that allowed comparison of different architectures.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks are designed to mimic a particular type of workload on a component or system.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Synthetic benchmarks do this by specially created programs that impose the workload on the component.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Application benchmarks run real-world programs on the system.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] While application benchmarks usually give a much better measure of real-world performance on a given system, synthetic benchmarks are useful for testing individual components, like a hard disk or networking device.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks are particularly important in CPU design, giving processor architects the ability to measure and make tradeoffs in microarchitectural decisions.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] For example, if a benchmark extracts the key algorithms of an application, it will contain the performance-sensitive aspects of that application.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Running this much smaller snippet on a cycle-accurate simulator can give clues on how to improve performance.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Since around 1995, the SPEC collection of benchmarks have become widely used.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Computer companies are known to tune their systems to improve performance on benchmark tests that are not representative of real world usage.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks have been improved to more closely mimic real world usage, so that any tuning carries over to application performance.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Software vendors also use benchmarks in their marketing, such as the "benchmark wars" between rival relational database makers in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Companies commonly report only those benchmarks (or aspects of benchmarks) that show their products in the best light.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] They also have been known to mis-represent the significance of benchmarks, again to show their products in the best possible light.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] When performance is critical, the only benchmark that matters is the target environment's application suite.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Features of benchmarking software may include recording/exporting the course of performance to a spreadsheet file, visualization such as drawing line graphs or color-coded tiles, and pausing the process to be able to resume without having to start over.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Benchmarking is not easy and often involves several iterative rounds in order to arrive at predictable, useful conclusions.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Interpretation of benchmarking data is also extraordinarily difficult.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] There are seven vital characteristics for benchmarks.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Representativeness: Benchmark performance metrics should be broadly accepted by industry and academia.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Equity: All systems should be fairly compared.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Repeatability: Benchmark results can be verified.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Cost-effectiveness: Benchmark tests are economical.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Scalability: Benchmark tests should work across systems possessing a range of resources from low to high.
[src:load-testing-deep/benchmark-computing] Transparency: Benchmark metrics should be easy to understand.
