[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] JMeter requires that your computing environment meets some minimum requirements.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] JMeter is compatible with Java 8 or higher.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] We highly advise you to install latest minor version of your major version for security and performance reasons.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Because JMeter uses only standard Java APIs, please do not file bug reports if your JRE fails to run JMeter because of JRE implementation issues.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] JMeter is a 100% Java application and should run correctly on any system that has a compliant Java implementation.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Operating systems tested with JMeter can be viewed on this page on JMeter wiki.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Even if your OS is not listed on the wiki page, JMeter should run on it provided that the JVM is compliant.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] If you plan on doing JMeter development, then you will need one or more optional packages listed below.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] If you want to build the JMeter source or develop JMeter plugins, then you will need a fully compliant JDK 8 or higher.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] JMeter comes with Apache's Xerces XML parser.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] You have the option of telling JMeter to use a different XML parser.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] To do so, include the classes for the third-party parser in JMeter's classpath, and update the jmeter.properties file with the full classname of the parser implementation.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] JMeter has extensive Email capabilities.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] It can send email based on test results, and has a POP3(S)/IMAP(S) sampler.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] To test a web server using SSL encryption (HTTPS), JMeter requires that an implementation of SSL be provided, as is the case with Sun Java 1.4 and above.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] If your version of Java does not include SSL support, then it is possible to add an external implementation.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Include the necessary encryption packages in JMeter's classpath.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Also, update system.properties to register the SSL Provider.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] JMeter HTTP defaults to protocol level TLS.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] This can be changed by editing the JMeter property https.default.protocol in jmeter.properties or user.properties.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] If the server requires a client certificate, this can be provided.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] There is also the SSL Manager, for greater control of certificates.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] The SMTP sampler can optionally use a local trust store or trust all certificates.
