[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] in the directory from which JMeter was launched, by default) instead.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Here is an example log4j2.xml file which defines two log appenders and loggers for each category.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] So, if you want to change the log level for org.apache.http category to debug level for instance, you can simply add (or uncomment) the following logger element in log4j2.xml file before launching JMeter.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] For more detail on how to configure log4j2.xml file, please see Apache Log4j 2 Configuration page.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Log level for specific categories or root logger can be overridden directly on the command line (instead of modifying log4j2.xml) as well.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] As JMeter uses SLF4J as logging API and Apache Log4j 2 as a logging framework since 3.2, not every log level used before 3.2 can match exactly with one of the new available log levels provided by SLF4J/Log4j2.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Therefore, please keep the following differences and new suggested practices in mind if you need to migrate any existing logging configurations and logging code.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] JMeter does not generally use pop-up dialog boxes for errors, as these would interfere with running tests.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Nor does it report any error for a mis-spelt variable or function; instead the reference is just used as is.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] If JMeter detects an error during a test, a message will be written to the log file.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] The log file name is defined in the log4j2.xml file (or using the -j option, see below).
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] It defaults to jmeter.log, and will be found in the directory from which JMeter was launched.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] The menu Options → Log Viewer displays the log file in a bottom pane on main JMeter window.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] In the GUI mode, the number of error/fatal messages logged in the log file is displayed at top-right.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] The command-line option -j jmeterlogfile allow to process after the initial properties file is read, and before any further properties are processed.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] It therefore allows the default of jmeter.log to be overridden.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] The jmeter scripts that take a test plan name as a parameter (e.g. jmeter-n.cmd) have been updated to define the log file using the test plan name, e.g. for the test plan Test27.jmx the log file is set to Test27.log.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] As well as recording errors, the jmeter.log file records some information about the test run.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] The log file can be helpful in determining the cause of an error, as JMeter does not interrupt a test to display an error dialogue.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Invoking JMeter as "jmeter -?" will print a list of all the command-line options.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Note: the JMeter log file name is formatted as a SimpleDateFormat (applied to the current date) if it contains paired single-quotes, .e.g.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] If the special name LAST is used for the -t, -j or -l flags, then JMeter takes that to mean the last test plan that was run in interactive mode.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] Prior to version 2.5.1, JMeter invoked System.exit() when a CLI mode test completed.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] To detect this situation, JMeter starts a new daemon thread just before it exits.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] This daemon thread waits a short while; if it returns from the wait, then clearly the JVM has not been able to exit, and the thread prints a message to say why.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] The property jmeter.exit.check.pause can be used to configure the delay before printing non-daemon threads.
[src:load-testing-deep/get-started] If set to 0 (default value), then JMeter does not print non-terminated threads at the end of the test.
